        <h2>What Cross-Model Optimisation Means</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Cross-model optimisation is the recognition that your brand's AI visibility is determined by its performance across an ecosystem of AI platforms, not by a single model — and that the most efficient path to broad visibility is building shared foundations rather than isolated per-platform strategies.</strong>
          A brand that is well-cited on Perplexity but invisible on Google AI Overviews has an AI visibility problem that a Perplexity-only strategy cannot solve.
        </p>

        <p>
          The five major AI platforms that most brands need to target in 2026 are: ChatGPT (OpenAI), Perplexity, Google Gemini / AI Overviews, Claude (Anthropic), and Microsoft Copilot (Bing-powered). These platforms serve different user bases, use different retrieval architectures, and weight different signals — but they share a common requirement: content must be structured, attributed, accessible, and authoritative to earn consistent citations.
        </p>

        <p>
          Cross-model optimisation sits within the broader <a href="/optimise-for-ai-platforms/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">optimising for specific AI platforms</a> topic cluster and is the strategic complement to platform-specific playbooks. It answers the question: what do you build once, to perform everywhere? The per-platform guides answer: what do you layer on top for each specific platform? The full strategic context sits within <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation</a> as a discipline.
        </p>

        <h3>Why Not Just Optimise for the Biggest Platform?</h3>
        <p>
          Platform market share in AI search is volatile and fragmented. Perplexity's user base skews towards high-value B2B researchers; Google AI Overviews reaches the widest consumer audience; Copilot is embedded in Microsoft 365 for enterprise users. A brand that optimises exclusively for ChatGPT may be invisible to the Perplexity user researching vendors before a purchasing decision. Cross-model optimisation is the risk-management answer to a fragmented platform landscape — it diversifies visibility rather than concentrating it in a single model's behaviour.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <section id="shared-foundation" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>The Shared Foundation: What Works Everywhere</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Approximately 80% of measurable AI citation gains come from a shared foundation of five practices that improve performance across every major platform simultaneously.</strong>
          These are not platform-specific optimisations — they are universal requirements that any AI system capable of retrieving and citing content will respond to.
        </p>

        <div class="not-prose mt-8 space-y-5">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Entity Authority</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              A well-defined brand entity — with a Wikidata record, consistent sameAs references, and accurate third-party descriptions — is the single most universally beneficial signal in cross-model optimisation. Every major platform uses entity resolution to identify and describe brands. A brand whose entity record is incomplete, inconsistent, or absent from knowledge graphs is described inaccurately or omitted entirely, regardless of how well-optimised its content is.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Citation-Ready Content Structure</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Self-contained passages, declarative topic sentences, and explicit headings that function as standalone labels are structural properties that improve citation rates across all platforms. They work because they reduce the interpretive overhead that any retrieval system — regardless of the underlying model — must apply to extract a citable answer from a document. For the full mechanics of this approach, see our page on <a href="/llm-context-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">LLM context optimisation</a>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Valid JSON-LD Schema</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Organisation, Article, FAQPage, and BreadcrumbList schemas in valid JSON-LD are processed by retrieval systems across all major platforms. Schema markup reduces parse ambiguity, signals content type and authority, and maps Q&A content directly onto the response format that generative platforms prefer. Deploying valid schema sitewide is a low-difficulty, high-impact action that benefits every platform simultaneously. For implementation detail, see our guide to <a href="/schema-markup-ai/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">schema markup for AI</a>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">AI Crawler Accessibility</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Content that is blocked to AI crawlers cannot appear in RAG-based responses on any platform. A correctly configured robots.txt that permits GPTBot, PerplexityBot, ClaudeBot, and Bingbot — alongside a complete, current sitemap — is the prerequisite for cross-model RAG visibility. An llms.txt file provides an additional signal that benefits all platforms supporting the standard.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Topical Authority Depth</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              A content cluster that covers a subject comprehensively — with pages addressing core concepts, sub-topics, adjacent questions, and specific use cases — signals domain expertise to all retrieval systems. Retrieval systems prefer sources that demonstrate systematic coverage of a topic over sources with a single high-quality page on a topic. Building topical depth through a structured content architecture (ROOT → NODE → SEED) is the most sustainable approach to cross-model authority.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>
