        <h2>Platform-by-Platform Profiles</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Each major AI platform has a distinct retrieval architecture, user base, and signal weighting — understanding these profiles allows brands to prioritise per-model investments on top of their shared foundation.</strong>
        </p>

        <h3>ChatGPT (OpenAI)</h3>
        <p>
          ChatGPT operates in two modes. Without Browse enabled, it relies entirely on parametric knowledge — information compressed into model weights during training. In this mode, brands with strong third-party coverage in the training corpus (press, Wikipedia, Wikidata, industry publications) surface reliably; brands without that coverage are absent regardless of their website's content quality. With Browse or GPT-4 with Search enabled, ChatGPT retrieves live web content and citations become directly influenced by content structure and schema. The split between user sessions with and without Browse is significant enough to require optimising for both modes.
        </p>

        <h3>Perplexity</h3>
        <p>
          Perplexity is the most RAG-intensive of the major platforms — it retrieves live web sources for almost every response and displays citations with source links prominently. This makes Perplexity the most immediately responsive platform to content structure and schema improvements. Brands that publish well-structured, self-contained content on accessible pages typically see measurable Perplexity citation improvements within weeks of deployment. Perplexity's user base is disproportionately high-intent — researchers, analysts, and professionals — making it high-value even with lower total traffic than Google.
        </p>

        <h3>Google Gemini and AI Overviews</h3>
        <p>
          Google AI Overviews are powered by Gemini and are deeply integrated with Google's traditional search index and Knowledge Graph. This means traditional SEO signals — domain authority, page authority, E-E-A-T signals, structured data, and indexation quality — are more directly relevant here than on any other AI platform. Brands with strong Google Search performance typically see corresponding AI Overviews visibility. The Key differentiator for Gemini-specific optimisation is Knowledge Graph presence: ensuring your brand entity is well-represented in Google's Knowledge Graph, particularly through Wikipedia, structured data, and verified Google Business profiles.
        </p>

        <h3>Claude (Anthropic)</h3>
        <p>
          Claude's citation behaviour in its Claude.ai interface favours sources with well-defined entity authority and clearly structured, self-contained content. Its training data emphasis on reliability and accuracy means brands with consistent, fact-dense content and verifiable entity records tend to surface more reliably than brands relying on narrative-heavy pages. Claude is increasingly used in enterprise contexts for research tasks, making visibility in Claude particularly valuable for B2B brands targeting high-value accounts.
        </p>

        <h3>Microsoft Copilot</h3>
        <p>
          Microsoft Copilot is powered by Bing's search and retrieval infrastructure, meaning Bing indexation quality is a direct prerequisite for Copilot visibility. Brands that neglect Bing indexation in favour of a Google-only strategy may have strong Google AI Overviews presence but weak Copilot visibility. Copilot's integration into Microsoft 365 products — Teams, Word, Outlook — gives it significant enterprise reach that is not fully reflected in public usage statistics.
        </p>
      </section>

