      <!-- Section 5 -->
      <section id="per-model-nuances" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Per-Model Nuances That Move the Needle</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Per-model nuances are the incremental optimisations that produce measurable citation gains on a specific platform, on top of the shared foundation that drives performance everywhere.</strong>
          They are not alternatives to the shared foundation — they are multipliers that amplify it.
        </p>

        <h3>For ChatGPT: Invest in Training Data Coverage</h3>
        <p>
          Because non-Browse ChatGPT relies on parametric knowledge, the highest-leverage per-model investment for ChatGPT visibility is third-party press and reference site coverage. Profiles on Crunchbase, G2, Capterra, and industry analyst reports all contribute to the training corpus coverage that determines whether ChatGPT "knows" your brand in the first place. This is a medium-to-long horizon investment, but its effects compound across successive OpenAI model versions.
        </p>

        <h3>For Perplexity: Maximise Structured Content and Crawler Access</h3>
        <p>
          Perplexity's retrieval-first architecture means that content structure optimisations produce the fastest and most measurable citation gains on this platform. Ensure PerplexityBot is permitted in robots.txt, pages are indexed, and content sections are structured as self-contained 150–400 word passages with explicit headings. Perplexity also surfaces FAQ content prominently — pages with valid FAQPage schema and well-formed Q&A sections consistently outperform pages without this structure.
        </p>

        <h3>For Google Gemini: Strengthen Knowledge Graph Presence</h3>
        <p>
          Google AI Overviews draw on Google's Knowledge Graph for entity resolution alongside its traditional search index. The highest-leverage per-model investment for Gemini is ensuring your entity is well-represented in the Knowledge Graph: a verified Google Business profile, consistent NAP data across citation sources, and Wikipedia/Wikidata entries that Google's systems can crawl and trust. Traditional Google SEO authority — page speed, Core Web Vitals, quality backlinks — also contributes to Gemini visibility in ways that are less relevant on non-Google platforms.
        </p>

        <h3>For Copilot: Do Not Neglect Bing</h3>
        <p>
          Microsoft Copilot's citation pool is Bing's index — not Google's. Brands that have submitted sitemaps exclusively to Google Search Console may be invisible to Copilot, regardless of their Google visibility. Submit your sitemap to Bing Webmaster Tools, monitor Bing crawl coverage, and ensure Bingbot is not blocked. This is the single highest-leverage per-model investment for Copilot, because it addresses a structural gap rather than a marginal signal optimisation.
        </p>

        <p>
          For deeper platform-specific playbooks, see the <a href="/optimise-for-ai-platforms/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">optimising for specific AI platforms</a> NODE, which covers each platform individually. For the LLM visibility concepts that underpin this work, see our page on <a href="/llm-visibility-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">LLM visibility optimisation</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6 -->
      <section id="measurement" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Measuring Cross-Model Performance</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Cross-model measurement is the discipline of tracking citation performance across all five major platforms systematically — using a consistent query set, consistent testing protocol, and platform-separated reporting.</strong>
          It is the feedback mechanism that turns a cross-model strategy from a set of theoretical best practices into a data-driven programme.
        </p>

        <p>
          A functional cross-model measurement programme requires three components. First, a target query set: 20–50 queries that represent the brand's core informational and commercial intent space — the questions its target audience asks AI systems. Second, a testing protocol: each query run on each target platform on a consistent cadence (weekly or fortnightly), with results recorded against a standard template that captures mention presence, mention accuracy, citation link inclusion, and the competitor brands mentioned alongside. Third, a reporting framework: platform-separated citation rate tracking that identifies which platforms are improving, which are stagnant, and which interventions are driving changes.
        </p>

        <p>
          The most common mistake in cross-model measurement is testing on a single platform and assuming results generalise. A brand can improve its Perplexity citation rate significantly through content structure work while remaining absent from Gemini AI Overviews due to weak Knowledge Graph presence. Only platform-separated tracking reveals these gaps. For the broader AI brand visibility measurement framework, see the <a href="/ai-brand-visibility/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AI brand visibility</a> guide.
        </p>
      </section>

